Patch Set 22:

yeah this is strange
maybe zuul is running in a virtualenv and overwrite /usr/bin/pip3 ?
or it's ansible ?

Could you try to use pip freeze from pip module instead of using popen ?

```
try:
    from pip._internal.operations import freeze
except ImportError:  # pip < 10.0
    from pip.operations import freeze

x = freeze.freeze()
print(x)
```

Or if you use popen use pip freeze call with module mechanism

```
[sys.executable, '-m', 'pip', 'freeze']

```

And see if we have different outputs?

Enough for a Friday afternoon, I'll try to find some workaround on Monday :).

[2] - https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=1733560
[3] - https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=1733003

Patch Set 1:

The information included looks good to me, but I have some questions after thinking about the current dci-check-change workflow, and as it may imply changes in the documentation, I will ask them here:

-In the example provided, an env variable is provided with -e. But, is it needed to provide all the variables to be used with -e, in case of being different of the default values defined in d-o-a-a? Or is it used the values provided in /etc/dci-openshift-app-agent/settings.yml? Regarding the second option, I have my concerns about that, because, if the change makes d-o-a-a being downloaded in a temp folder and d-o-a-a runs based on that code, I think variables from /etc/dci-openshift-app-agent/settings.yml are not used, but just to clarify that.
-In case of having a d-o-a-a change with depends-on clauses, depending on changes in repos like dallas-pipelines, inventories, etc., are the variables defined in that repos used in the jobs run by dci-check-change/test-runner? Or, again, do we need to provide them in a different way? (e.g. using -e). Because, of course, we are running the jobs in an environment different than dallas, where the pipelines are not needed in fact.
-In case of requiring using the CNF Cert Suite or the test_tnf_example, as we are always running the basic_example, do we need, again, to change some variables to make it work? Or should dci-check-change be modified to allow this?

Patch Set 34: -Code-Review

hmm that's weird, the last job failed in the same point that this previous job: https://www.distributed-ci.io/jobs/ea0e6e7c-873d-4ef2-9c26-c2afff455e6a/jobStates, due to the build != ga condition in "Install missing from previous version" task, which prevents the installation of missing operators such as the performance-addon-operator

```
TASK [operators-mirror : Install missing from previous version] ****************
1s
task path: /home/dciteam/github/dallas-pipelines-pr126-f98a6a6491f91c90d483d3fe02499527/dci-openshift-agent/roles/operators-mirror/tasks/build-catalog-index.yml:57

```

I guess this should be checked, so for the moment I will remove code-review

Patch Set 34:

Just for my understanding, why the build must not be ga (or candidate) in order to install the missing operators?

Patch Set 34:

If the version is GA we have to know if operators are missing.

The GA version must work without any tweaks.

Patch Set 34:

> Patch Set 34:
> 
> If the version is GA we have to know if operators are missing.
> 
> The GA version must work without any tweaks.

Then I believe there may be a conflict with pre-run task "set build:ga when build:candidate" (https://github.com/redhat-cip/dci-openshift-agent/blob/1a38d0e4af2d50558934813331d9e5040ac7b696/plays/pre-run.yml#L55).

Again, I'm not sure of this, but it looks like the operators may be missing if the release is a candidate, right? But the task above will cause the agent to treat candidate releases as ga, which may be the cause for the current failure.

Patch Set 34:

Just for completeness, you can see in the job the agent identifies the build as candidate at:

https://www.distributed-ci.io/jobs/e6965934-6c5b-4b84-b8ad-19a83f8bccd1/jobStates#a4417484-ca51-48a8-bbc2-69ae9b351655:file32

And then it's moved to ga at:

https://www.distributed-ci.io/jobs/e6965934-6c5b-4b84-b8ad-19a83f8bccd1/jobStates#a4417484-ca51-48a8-bbc2-69ae9b351655:file35

Patch Set 34:

> Patch Set 34:
> 
> > Patch Set 34:
> > 
> > If the version is GA we have to know if operators are missing.
> > 
> > The GA version must work without any tweaks.
> 
> Then I believe there may be a conflict with pre-run task "set build:ga when build:candidate" (https://github.com/redhat-cip/dci-openshift-agent/blob/1a38d0e4af2d50558934813331d9e5040ac7b696/plays/pre-run.yml#L55).
> 
> Again, I'm not sure of this, but it looks like the operators may be missing if the release is a candidate, right? But the task above will cause the agent to treat candidate releases as ga, which may be the cause for the current failure.

What Pierre mentioned is correct, a candidate build should be considered GA build, because a candidate will only receive bug fixes and eventually becomes GA.

Additionally the changes not only has to do with operators, but also installation in itself.

Looking at the code helps to understand better this situation, rather than looking at the output of the job.

For example here it's explained that part of the considerations between GA and candidate:

https://github.com/redhat-cip/dci-openshift-agent/blob/master/plays/pre-run.yml#L51-L58

The initial reason to do build ga when is a candidate is due to a path in the URL of the installer, here you can see that (for old components) the URL is built based on the build:

https://github.com/redhat-cip/dci-openshift-agent/blob/master/roles/mirror-ocp-release/tasks/fetch.yml#L30

But we also took advantage of the build to determine whether a particular version of operators should be used or not:

https://github.com/redhat-cip/dci-openshift-agent/blob/master/roles/operators-mirror/tasks/mirror.yml#L2-L12

I understand that you mentioned that the change in the prerun "hides" the build later in the run, but for the operators we shouldn't care if a build is GA or candidate, it should be the same for both.  The only case we care is for nightly build, called dev.

hth

> The initial reason to do build ga when is a candidate is due to a path in the URL of the installer, here you can see that (for old components) the URL is built based on the build:
>

> 
> I understand that you mentioned that the change in the prerun "hides" the build later in the run, but for the operators we shouldn't care if a build is GA or candidate, it should be the same for both.  The only case we care is for nightly build, called dev.

Then, if I'm following, that means the error in the last jobs is accepted, according to design, and caused by a buggy release candidate.

Abandoned

Exactly Nacho, that's why I'm abandoning this change for now.

This patch could be tested through an SNO job isn't it?

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

> Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1
> 
> This patch could be tested through an SNO job isn't it?

We can launch an OCP on libvirt or SNO to test d-o-a-a (we will prefer SNO already running to speed thinks up), but I'm not sure this patch will be tested either way. I think this is one of those chicken-and-egg patches hard to test because this .spec builds the rpm, but when this patch is tested the produced RPM is not installed in the system. I might be wrong, I've seen we do a bunch of git clone steps to test the change, but I haven't seen it installs a temporal RPM in a cage or something.

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1
> 
> > Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1
> > 
> > This patch could be tested through an SNO job isn't it?
> 
> We can launch an OCP on libvirt or SNO to test d-o-a-a (we will prefer SNO already running to speed thinks up), but I'm not sure this patch will be tested either way. I think this is one of those chicken-and-egg patches hard to test because this .spec builds the rpm, but when this patch is tested the produced RPM is not installed in the system. I might be wrong, I've seen we do a bunch of git clone steps to test the change, but I haven't seen it installs a temporal RPM in a cage or something.

I fear the same, that running a test will not help. In fact, when testing CR 22648, must-gather works correctly because it was running the code downloaded from gerrit, so in this case, if we launch a job, it will happen the same: the job will be launched from the code downloaded and, as scripts/get-logs is present, it will be executed. 
I think we will have to merge the code, then update dci-openshift-app-agent in the servers to check if it works or not.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

I don't think we need to worry about testing this particular change in any environment, the dci-rpm-build-el8 check takes care of building the RPM, and it passed. That's check takes care of validating the spec and building the RPM.

The functionality has been tested previously and it worked, this is good to merge 😊
